The '''Oghur''' or '''Oğuric'''{{sfn|Golden|2011|p=30}} languages (also known as '''Bulgar''', '''Pre-Proto Bulgaric''',{{sfn|Golden|2011|p=39}} or '''Lir-Turkic''' and '''r-Turkic''') are a branch of the [[Turkic languages|Turkic language family]]. The only extant member of the group is the [[Chuvash language]]. Languages from this family were spoken in some nomadic tribal confederations, such as those of the [[Onogurs]], [[Bulgars]], and [[Khazars]].{{sfn|Golden|2011|p=239}} Some scholars consider [[Hunnic language|Hunnic]] a similar language<ref>{{cite book |last=Pritsak |first=Omeljan |author-link=Omeljan Pritsak |date=1982 |title=The Hunnic Language of the Attila Clan  |url=http://projects.iq.harvard.edu/files/huri/files/vvi_n4_dec1982.pdf |publisher=[[Harvard Ukrainian Research Institute]] |place=Cambridge, Massachusetts |volume=IV |issue=4 |pages=470 |issn=0363-5570}}</ref> and refer to this extended grouping as '''Hunno-Bulgarian'''.<ref>{{cite book|author-first=Omeljan|last=Pritsak|chapter=The Proto-Bulgarian Military Inventory Inscriptions|title=Turkic-Bulgarian-Hungarian relations|year=1981|location=Budapest}}</ref>

==History==
The Oghuric languages are a distinct group of the [[Turkic languages]], standing in contrast to [[Common Turkic languages|Common Turkic]]. Today they are represented only by [[Chuvash language|Chuvash]]. Extinct Oghuric languages include [[Bulgar language|Bulgar]] and [[Khazar language|Khazar]].{{sfn|Golden|1992|p=95–96}} There is no consensus among linguists on the relation between Oghuric and Common Turkic, and several questions remain unsolved:
*Are they parallel branches of [[Proto-Turkic]] (3000-500 BC) and, if so, which branch is more archaic?
*Does Oghuric represents Archaic Turkic before phonetic changes in 100-400 AD and was it a separate language?{{sfn|Golden|2011|p=30}}

==Features==
The Oghuric languages are also known as "-r Turkic" because the final consonant in certain words is ''r'', not ''z'' as in Common Turkic.{{sfn|Golden|1992|p=95–96}} {{lang-cv|вăкăр}} - {{lang-tr|öküz}} - {{lang-tt|үгез}} - {{lang-en|ox}}. Hence the name ''[[Turkic tribal confederations|Oghur]]'' corresponds ''Oghuz'' in Common Turkic.{{sfn|Golden|2011|p=30}} Other correspondences are Com. ''š'' : Oghur ''l'' (''tâš'' : ''tâl'', 'stone'); ''s'' > ''š''; ''*č'' > ''ś''; ''k/q'' > ''ğ''; ''y'' > ''j, ś''; ''d, δ'' > ''δ'' > ''z'' (10th cent.) > ''r'' (13th cent.)"; ''ğd'' > ''z'' > ''r'' (14th cent.); ''a'' > ''ı'' (after 9th cent.).{{sfn|Golden|1992|p=20, 96}}{{sfn|Golden|2011|p=30, 236–239}}

[[Denis Sinor]] believes that the difference means that those tribes could not have come from lands like [[Mongolia]], which uses a ''-z'' language.{{sfn|Golden|2011|p=29}} However, there many loanwords in [[Mongolic languages|Mongolic]] from Oghuric, like Mong. ''ikere'', Oghur. ''*ikir'', Hung. ''iker'', Comm. ''ikiz'' (twins).{{sfn|Golden|2011|p=30}} It is believed that they lived in the Mongolian borderlands before the 5th century.{{sfn|Golden|2011|p=31}}

The Oghuric tribes are often connected with the [[Hungarians]] whose ethnonym is usually derived from Onoghurs (> (H)ungars).{{sfn|Golden|1992|p=102–103}} The Hungarians were mixed [[Finno-Ugric peoples|Finno-Ugric]] and Turkic, with strong Oghuric-Bulgar and Khazar influences.{{sfn|Golden|1992|p=262}}{{sfn|Golden|2011|p=333}} Hungarian has many borrowings from Turkic and Oghuric languages:{{sfn|Golden|1992|p=259–260}} Hung. ''tenger'', Oghur. ''*tengir'', Comm. ''tengiz'' (sea),{{sfn|Golden|2011|p=30}} Hung. ''gyűrű'', Oghur. ''jürük'', Comm. ''yüzük'' (ring),{{sfn|Golden|2011|p=164}} and terms of equestrian culture ''ló'' (horse), ''nyereg'' (saddle), ''fék'' (bridle), ''ostor'' (whip).{{sfn|Golden|1992|p=259}} A number of Hungarian loanwords were borrowed before the 9th century, shown by ''sz-'' (< Oğ. ''ś-'') rather than Comm. ''gy-'' (< Oğ. ''ǰ-''): example Hung. ''szél'', Oghur. ''*śäl'', Chuv. ''śil'',  Comm. ''yel'' (wind), Hung. ''szűcs'' (tailor), Hung. ''szőlő'' (grapes).{{sfn|Golden|2011|p=164}}

